  "diary": "Woke to that steady Seattle rain—the kind that makes you want to stay in bed but also somehow clears your head. Coffee at home tasted better than usual. Ladro was crowded this morning, everyone avoiding the weather, I guess. Took the long way to the studio through Ballard since the bridge was a mess; the detour felt right, actually. Had two solid clients back-to-back. The first piece was intricate, really focused work. Grabbed pho at Thanh Huong to warm up between sessions. Popped into Shorty's for a bit—found an old Pentax I've been eyeing, didn't buy it but maybe soon. Afternoon was mine. Spent an hour in the darkroom with last weekend's film, something about watching the prints emerge in the red light always feels like meditation. Made pasta on the porch, rain had stopped by then. Just felt like a day that moved right, you know?",
  "thought_process": "The rain and bridge closure could've derailed everything, but I chose the scenic route early—Ballard's calmer anyway, and it put me in a better headspace before the clients arrived. Two detailed sessions back-to-back meant I needed to stay sharp and present; lunch at Thanh Huong was practical but also intentional, keeping warm and focused. After work, I felt the pull toward the darkroom instead of just crashing, which told me I had energy left. The vintage camera shop was a small indulgence, a reminder that I'm still collecting and creating outside of ink. By evening, I was genuinely content—tired but satisfied. The grey day didn't drag me down; it actually anchored me.",
